headline: Starbucks’ Worker Strike Is Growing. The Stock Sheds 6% Since Last Week.
summary: Starbucks  shares have tumbled more than 6% since last Monday’s closing price after the union representing thousands of its store workers announced a strike to protest stalled negotiations with the company.  More locations in Colorado, Ohio, and Pennsylvania joined on Saturday, followed by union workers in Missouri, New Jersey, and New York on Sunday.  The Workers United union, representing more than 10,000 Starbucks workers across 525 stores, said the strike could reach “hundreds of stores” by Tuesday.

headline: Starbucks strike expands, closes nearly 60 US stores
summary: A five-day strike by Starbucks baristas had closed 59 stores as of Monday afternoon, according to the union organizing the workers.  The strike, which began Friday in Los Angeles, Chicago and Starbucks' hometown of Seattle, spread Monday to stores in Boston, Dallas and Portland, Ore. Workers in New York, Denver, Pittsburgh and other cities had also joined the strike over the weekend.  Starbucks Workers United, which began the unionization effort in 2021, said Starbucks has failed to honor a commitment made in February to reach a labor agreement this year.
